{{about||the Australian artist and journalist|David Henry Souter|the former U.S. Supreme Court Justice|David Souter}}
{{Infobox artist | bgcolour = #6495ED | name = David Suter | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1949}} | birth_place = [[Bethesda, Maryland]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Americans|American]] | field = [[Illustration]], Painting, Sculpture | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | influenced by = [[M. C. Escher]]<ref name=Kraus /> | influenced = | awards = }} '''David Suter''' (born 1949)<ref name=Lyman>Lyman, Rick. [https://www.nytimes.com/1997/07/27/movies/rendering-hamlet-with-pen-in-hand.html?pagewanted=all "FILM: Rendering 'Hamlet' With Pen in Hand,"] ''New York Times'' (July 27, 1997).</ref> is an [[American citizenship|American]] artist known for his many years producing [[Editorial cartoonist|editorial illustrations]] for clients such as ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]''. Known as "Suterisms"<ref name=People /> or "visual [[koans]]",<ref name=3x3>[http://3x3mag.com/about/currentissue "Current Issue,"] ''3x3 Magazine''. Accessed Dec. 2, 2015.</ref> his illustrations are notable for their use of [[bistable perception]], in which Suter combines multiple images and concepts into a single image.<ref name=People>Van Biema, David H. [http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20092214,00.html "Look Twice! Illustrator David Suter Uses Visual Puns to Make His Points,"] ''People'' Vol. 24, No. 21 (November 18, 1985).</ref> Suter is also an accomplished fine art painter and sculptor.
== Biography and illustration career == Suter grew up in [[Bethesda, Maryland]], the son of Richard Sturgis Suter, who worked in the CIA, and Angela Phillips Suter, an artist. He was influenced early on by the [[Mathematical art|mathematically]] inspired work of [[M. C. Escher]],<ref name=Lyman /> but never had any formal art training.<ref name=People />
Suter attended a number of different colleges, not graduating from any of them.<ref name=Lyman /> Drafted into the [[U.S. Army|Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]], he spent his deployment in [[West Germany]].<ref name=Lyman /> t Upon returning to the U.S., Suter got work at ''The Washington Post'' as an illustrator, for a while working as a [[courtroom artist]] during the [[Watergate scandal]] trials.<ref name=Jenkins1 />
Suter was awarded a [[Michigan Journalism Fellowship]] in 1977, where he spent a year studying fine art, philosophy, and history<ref>[http://www.mjfellows.org/fellows/1978.html "Past Fellows: 1977–1978,"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028152543/http://www.mjfellows.org/fellows/1978.html |date=2015-10-28 }} Knight-Wallace Fellows at Michigan website. Accessed Dec. 2, 2015.</ref> at the [[University of Michigan]]. Upon completion of the fellowship, in 1978, Suter moved to New York City to pursue editorial illustration full-time. He quickly become sought-after by such publications as ''The New York Times'' (both on the [[op-ed page]] and [[The New York Times Book Review|the book review]]), ''Time'' magazine (for whom he did a number of covers), ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'', and the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''.<ref name=3x3 />
In a mid-1980s magazine profile, Suter described his work this way: {{cquote|I don't think of them as puns. I like to think of them as equations. Every story suggests a certain number of images. And then there are other images, the visual clichés that are in everybody's mind and sort of make up their mental scenery, like [[the Pentagon]], the [[Statue of Liberty]], or the [[Christian cross|Cross]]. My mind is like a [[slot machine]]: You pull the lever and eventually one of the images from the article comes to rest next to a cliché that looks something like it. . . . It's a little like [[algebra]]. I try to combine the two images through a process of finding similarities and canceling out dissimilar aspects.<ref name=People />}}
For many years, Suter has been working on creating a full-length animation of the complete text of [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Hamlet]]''.<ref name=Lyman /><ref name=Kraus>Kraus, Jerelle. ''All the Art That's Fit to Print (And Some That Wasn't): Inside The New York Times Op-Ed Page'' (Columbia University Press, 2013), p. 82.</ref>
In the late 2000s he retired from editorial illustration to work full-time on his painting and sculpture practices.
== Fine art == The first exhibition of Suter's fine art — which he terms "[[Constructivism (art)|Constructivist]] [[Expressionist art|Expressionist]]"<ref name=Jenkins1>Jenkins, Mark. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/painter-and-sculpter-david-suters-homespun-art-at-gallery-a/2011/11/16/gIQAKoTrVN_story.html "Style: Painter and sculpter <nowiki>[sic]</nowiki> David Suter’s homespun art at Gallery A,"] ''The Washington Post'' (November 17, 2011).</ref> — was in 1996 at the Morgan Rank Gallery in [[East Hampton, New York]].<ref name=Lyman /> He is represented by Gallery A and Alex Gallery in Washington, D.C.<ref name=Jenkins2>Jenkins, Mark. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/serbian-authorities-detain-dc-artist-gallery-owner-seize-dozens-of-artworks/2011/11/21/gIQAULaXjN_story.html "Style: Serbian authorities detain D.C. artist, gallery owner, seize dozens of artworks,"] ''The Washington Post'' (November 21, 2011).</ref>
In 2011, he was arrested and detained in [[Serbia]] while transporting his paintings from [[France]] to [[Romania]] for a gallery show in [[Bucharest]].<ref name=Print>Heller, Steven. [http://www.printmag.com/imprint/david-suter-detained-in-serbia/ "David Suter Detained in Serbia,"] ''Print'' magazine (November 22, 2011).</ref><ref name=Jenkins2 />
== Personal life == Suter has four daughters: Valerie, Georgia, Charlotte and Olivia.<ref name=Lyman />
== Quotes == {{cquote|He doesn't simply create a striking accompaniment to the text, like most of my artists. His method actually transforms the author's argument into a new visual symbol. . . . No one can do them like him. — [[Jerelle Kraus]], long-time art director of ''The New York Times'' op-ed page<ref name=People />}}
{{cquote|Even his mediocre things are good, and his best things are brilliant. — [[Steven Heller (design writer)|Steven Heller]]<ref name=People />}}
{{cquote|In some cases David gets to the essence of a subject more quickly and economically than the writer. If people say it's visual trickery, it's bloody good visual trickery. His work will stand up. — [[Nigel Holmes]]<ref name=People />}}
