[[File:Equichordal-center.svg|thumb|Curve (red) with two chords (black), intersecting in the equichordal point.]] In [[geometry]], an '''equichordal point''' is a point defined relative to a [[Convex set|convex]] plane curve such that all [[Chord (geometry)|chords]] passing through the point are equal in length. Two common figures with equichordal points are the [[circle]] and the [[limaçon]]. It is impossible for a curve to have more than one equichordal point.
==Equichordal curves== A curve is called equichordal when it has an equichordal point.<ref>{{citation |author=Steven G. Krantz |title=Techniques of Problem Solving |publisher=[[American Mathematical Society]] |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-8218-0619-7 }}</ref> Such a curve may be constructed as the [[pedal curve]] of a [[curve of constant width]].<ref>{{citation | last = Kelly | first = Paul J. | authorlink = Paul Kelly (mathematician) | journal = [[American Mathematical Monthly]] | mr = 0092168 | pages = 333–336 | title = Curves with a kind of constant width | volume = 64 | year = 1957 | doi=10.2307/2309594}}.</ref> For instance, the pedal curve of a [[circle]] is either another circle (when the center of the circle is the pedal point) or a [[limaçon]]; both are equichordal curves.
==Multiple equichordal points== {{main|equichordal point problem}} In 1916 Fujiwara proposed the question of whether a curve could have two equichordal points (offering in the same paper a proof that three or more is impossible). Independently, a year later, Blaschke, Rothe and Weitzenböck posed the same question.<ref>W. Blaschke, W. Rothe, and R. Weitztenböck. Aufgabe 552. Arch. Math. Phys., 27:82, 1917.</ref> The problem remained unsolved until it was finally proven impossible in 1996 by [[Marek Rychlik]].<ref>{{citation | last = Rychlik | first = Marek | doi = 10.1090/S1079-6762-96-00015-7 | issue = 3 | journal = Electronic Research Announcements of the American Mathematical Society | mr = 1426720 | pages = 108–123 | title = The equichordal point problem | volume = 2 | year = 1996}}.</ref><ref>{{citation | last = Rychlik | first = Marek R. | doi = 10.1007/s002220050161 | issue = 1 | journal = Inventiones Mathematicae | mr = 1464869 | pages = 141–212 | title = A complete solution to the equichordal point problem of Fujiwara, Blaschke, Rothe and Weitzenböck | volume = 129 | year = 1997| bibcode = 1997InMat.129..141R }}.</ref> Despite its elementary formulation, the [[equichordal point problem]] was difficult to solve. [[Rychlik's theorem]] is proved by methods of advanced complex analysis and algebraic geometry and it is 72 pages long.
